            }
          ],
          "defaultServings": 4
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Poach the haddock",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Put the haddock skin-down in a wide saucepan. Pour over the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{whole-milk}} of whole milk",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and bring to a gentle simmer. Poach for 8-10 minutes until the fish flakes easily. Remove the haddock, peel away the skin, and flake the flesh into large pieces, discarding any bones. Reserve the poaching milk.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make the sauce and filling",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Melt ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{unsalted-butter}} of butter",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " in a saucepan over medium heat. Soften the onion for 8 minutes, then add the leeks and cook for 3 minutes. Stir in ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{plain-flour}} of flour",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and cook for 2 minutes. Gradually add the reserved poaching milk, stirring constantly. Add the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{double-cream}} of cream",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and simmer for 5 minutes until thickened. Season with ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{black-pepper}}",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " only; the haddock provides the salt. Fold in the flaked fish. Cool the filling completely before assembling.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Top and bake",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat the oven to 200°C (180°C fan). Spoon the cooled filling into a deep pie dish. Roll or unroll the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{puff-pastry}} of puff pastry",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and lay it over the top, pressing the edges to the rim. Trim off the excess. Cut a steam vent in the centre. Brush with beaten egg. Bake for 35-40 minutes until the pastry is deeply golden and the filling is bubbling at the vent.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "rows": [
            {
              "fix": "Cool the filling completely. Set a pie funnel or upturned egg cup in the centre of the dish to support the pastry.",
              "cause": "Filling was still warm when the pastry was laid on, causing steam to detach the lid",
              "symptom": "Pastry lid lifts off or sinks into the filling"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Never add salt to the sauce; the poaching milk carries enough. Taste before seasoning.",
              "cause": "Smoked haddock releases a lot of salt into the poaching milk",
              "symptom": "Sauce is too salty"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Leave the filled dish at room temperature for 20 minutes before topping and baking.",
              "cause": "Filling was refrigerator-cold when it went into the oven",
              "symptom": "Pastry is golden but sauce is cold in the centre"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Poach just until the fish flakes when pressed; fold gently in one or two turns, not repeatedly.",
              "cause": "Overpoached or overhandled when folding",
              "symptom": "Haddock breaks into very fine pieces and disappears into the sauce"
            }
          ]
        },
        "content": []
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Smoked haddock and leek pie sits at the intersection of the Scottish fish pie tradition and the everyday British comfort kitchen. It is a winter and early spring dish, suited to cold evenings and simple serving with nothing more than a green salad.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
